#Text=Anthony Morgan of Freshwater
#Text=Major Anthony Morgan ( died 1729 ) of Freshwater , Isle of Wight was a British Army officer , and Whig politician who sat in the House of Commons between 1695 and 1729 .
#Text=He was a Lieutenant-Governor of the Isle of Wight ,
#Text=Early life
#Text=Morgan 's parentage is unknown .
#Text=He married Catherine Urry , daughter and heir of Thomas Urry of Freshwater , Isle of Wight by 1691 , and by the marriage , acquired the manor of Freshwater .
#Text=He was an army officer in the Life Guards and was Brigadier and lieutenant by 1691 .
#Text=He was exempt and captain in 1692 , guidon and major in 1694 and cornet and senior major in 1697 . [ 1 ]
#Text=Political career

#Text=Morgan began building up an electoral influence at Newtown and Yarmouth , and came into conflict with the new governor Lord Cutts who tried to bring the island 's constituencies under government control .
#Text=At the 1695 English general election Morgan was elected Member of Parliament for Yarmouth and signed the Association .
#Text=He voted for fixing the price of guineas at 22 shillings in March 1695 and for the attainder of Sir John Fenwick on 25 November 1696 .
#Text=Under an electoral accord of 1697 , he was returned unopposed at the 1698 English general election , and voted in support of a standing army on 18 January 1699 .
#Text=He was returned unopposed again at the two general elections of 1701 and was classed as a Whig .
#Text=In 1702 , he was appointed Lieutenant-Governor of the Isle of Wight , much to the annoyance of Lord Cutts , who still held a grudge against him and tried to prevent the appointment .
#Text=At the 1702 English general election , Morgan was returned unopposed for Yarmouth again .
#Text=He was returned again at the 1705 English general election and voted for the Court candidate as Speaker on 25 October 1705 .
#Text=He also supported the Court over the place clause of the regency bill in February 1706 .
#Text=He was returned as a Whig MP for Yarmouth at the 1708 British general election and voted for the impeachment of Dr Sacheverell in 1710 .
#Text=He lost his seat and his position with the change of government at the 1710 British general election and did not regain them until after the Hanoverian succession . [ 1 ]
#Text=At the 1715 general election Morgan stood as a Whig at Yarmouth and Newport .
#Text=He was returned at Newport and though initially defeated at Yarmouth was then seated after a petition on 12 April 1717 .
#Text=Thereupon he yielded the seat at Newport .
#Text=He voted consistently for the Whig Administration .
#Text=He was Lieutenant-Governor of the Isle of Wight again from 1715 until his death and was also governor of Cowes Castle from 1715 until his death in 1729 .
#Text=He was returned again at Yarmouth in the 1722 British general election .
#Text=In the 1727 British general election he changed seats and was returned unopposed at Lymington . [ 2 ]
#Text=Death and legacy
#Text=Morgan died on 19 April 1729 .
#Text=He left six sons and a daughter , but disinherited his eldest son , and left the Freshwater estate to his five younger sons . [ 2 ]
#Text=His second son Maurice was MP for Yarmouth .
